  "slug": "roast-pheasant",
  "title": "Roast Pheasant",
  "subtitle": "Barded with bacon, roasted briefly at high heat, and served with bread sauce and watercress",
  "excerpt": "Pheasant is the most widely available British game bird, in season from October through February. Roasted at high heat for 30 minutes and barded with streaky bacon, the breast stays moist while the legs cook through. Bread sauce and game chips are the traditional accompaniments.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Jane Grigson, English Food (1974): roast pheasant with bread sauce. Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136: roasting game birds. Traditional British game cookery.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pheasant is a lean bird. The breast in particular has almost no fat marbling, which means it can go from moist to dry in a matter of minutes. The traditional solution is ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "barding",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr3bf00000hcv4uvtpkj2x"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": ": laying streaky rashers across the breast to self-baste as they render. The rashers come off for the last 10 minutes to give the breast skin a chance to colour.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The traditional accompaniments are ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "bread sauce",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr3bfn0001hcv45geyfezy"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " and game chips (thinly sliced, deep-fried potatoes), with watercress on the plate for colour. The method below includes bread sauce made alongside the bird, using the same saucepan.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "What you need",
            "type": "text"
          }
