      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bard and roast",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 220°C (200°C fan). Pat the bird dry. Rub the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{unsalted-butter}} of butter",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " over the legs and tuck the thyme sprigs into the cavity. Season lightly with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sea-salt-flakes}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{black-pepper}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Lay the bacon rashers in overlapping strips across the entire breast. Roast for 20 minutes, then remove the bacon and return the bird for 10 minutes to colour the breast skin. A probe at the deepest point of the thigh should read 75°C.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the bread sauce",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "While the bird roasts, put the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{whole-milk}} of whole milk",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " in a small saucepan with the clove-studded onion halves. Heat until barely simmering, then remove from the heat and leave for 20 minutes to infuse. Remove the onion, add the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{breadcrumbs-fresh}} of breadcrumbs",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and stir over low heat until the sauce thickens to a loose porridge consistency. Season, then stir in the double cream if using.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Rest and make the pan gravy",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Transfer the pheasant to a warm board and rest for 10 minutes. Add ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{stock-chicken}} of chicken stock",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " to the roasting pan and scrape up the fond over medium heat. Simmer for 3 minutes, season, and strain. Carve at the table: the breast comes off the bone in two lobes; each person gets one breast and one leg.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "Keep the bacon on for the full 20 minutes. Pull the bird at 75°C on the probe, not by time alone.",
              "cause": "Bacon was removed too early, or the bird was overcooked past 80°C",
              "symptom": "Breast is dry and colourless"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Once the breast is at 72°C, cut the legs away and return them to the oven for 10 more minutes while the breast rests on the board.",
              "cause": "Pheasant legs are dense and carry-over temperature from the breast does not solve them",
              "symptom": "Legs are undercooked while the breast is done"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add crumbs gradually, stirring as you go. If lumpy, pass through a sieve.",
              "cause": "Breadcrumbs added too quickly or the milk was too hot",
              "symptom": "Bread sauce is lumpy"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Request a younger bird or one hung for 3 days rather than 7. The season (October through February) affects flavour: early-season birds are milder.",
              "cause": "Pheasant was hung for too long; older birds have a stronger flavour",
              "symptom": "The bird tastes very gamey"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Roast pheasant with bread sauce is the centre of British game-bird cookery. The combination has been unchanged for two centuries: the creaminess of the bread sauce against the leaner, more complex flavour of the bird, with the crunch of game chips or roast potatoes alongside. It is an autumn and winter table, hedgerow-to-plate.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
